# Time and Work – Quick Revision Sheet

## 1. Basic Concept

If a person completes a work in **N days**:

Work done in **1 day = 1 / N**

Example:
A completes work in 5 days

1 day work = 1/5

Total work = 1

---

## 2. Work Done Together

If A takes **x days** and B takes **y days**:

(A + B) one day work =

1/x + 1/y

Time together =

1 / (1/x + 1/y)

Example:
A = 6 days
B = 3 days

1 day work = 1/6 + 1/3 = 1/2

Time required = 2 days

---

## 3. LCM Method (Fastest for Aptitude)

Take **LCM of individual days as Total Work**.

Example:
A = 6 days
B = 3 days

Total Work = LCM(6,3) = 6

Efficiency:

A = 1 unit/day
B = 2 units/day

Together = 3 units/day

Time = 6 / 3 = **2 days**

---

## 4. Worker Leaving Problems

Steps:

1. Assume total work using **LCM**.
2. Calculate work done until someone leaves.
3. Remaining work done by remaining workers.

Example:
A = 10 days
B = 15 days

LCM = 30

Efficiency:

A = 3
B = 2

Together = 5

If both work 3 days:

Work done = 3 × 5 = 15

Remaining = 15

A alone:

Time = 15 / 3 = **5 days**

Total time = **8 days**

---

## 5. Efficiency Concept

Efficiency is **inversely proportional to time**.

If:

A takes 10 days
B takes 5 days

Efficiency ratio:

A : B = 1/10 : 1/5 = 1 : 2

So **B is twice as efficient as A**.

---

## 6. Workers vs Time Relation

Workers × Days = Constant

If workers increase → days decrease.

Example:
10 workers finish work in 12 days.

20 workers will take:

(10 × 12) / 20 = **6 days**

---

## 7. Pipes and Cisterns

Same as Time & Work.

Pipe filling = **positive work**
Pipe emptying = **negative work**

Example:
Pipe A fills tank in 6 hrs
Pipe B empties in 12 hrs

Net work per hour:

1/6 − 1/12 = 1/12

Tank fills in **12 hours**

---

## 8. Quick Tricks for Placements

• Always try **LCM method first**
• Convert time into **efficiency**
• Use **unit work approach**
• Leaving problems → calculate **remaining work**
• Pipes → treat emptying as **negative work**

---

